\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Your name please?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Allan Rees, 21 Denton Grove, Liverpool 6. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16457928 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14951568\charrsid19052  in 1940. Born 17 - 08 - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname metricconverter}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname ProductID}{\xmlattrvalue 1904. In}}}1904. In{\*\xmlclose} Liverpool.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 How many years did you live in the house in which you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
About two houses in the first - about two years rather in the first house, and then moved to Bootle - near Liverpool - to be nearer to my father's work at Tillotsons, about 1906.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Can you continue with your moves 'til the end of 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
Yes. Well as I said we - my father - we moved to Bootle to be near my father's work at Tillotsons in 1906. And then as mother had chest trouble the doctor recommended}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8934838\charrsid19052 
 moving away from Bottle's smok}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
y air. We lived near - just behind Bryant and Mays match factory. As a result we moved to Egremont on the other side of the river and father commuted as they call it now by ferry and over head railway each day in spit
e of the expense but mother got fully better. Father died 19 - twenty-seventh of June 1916. Mother sold the remains of the home for thirty shillings and went to live in London at me grandfather's invitation.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 How many brothers and sisters did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
Did - did you want me to finish what I'd written? I've written a little bit there. Yes. Mother could not settle there in London. So we came back to lodgings with a friend in Liverpool and some months later obtained a four roomed house in Liverpool w
here we remained until 1918. Now do you want to know anything about the - the bit in London. I was in the air raids - the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8934838\charrsid19052 z}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 e}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8934838\charrsid19052 p}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 pelin raids in London. Would that be of any interest? Well I can remember quite vividly seeing the zep}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8934838\charrsid19052 p}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 elins and shrapnel - gun sho
t round them, the search lights on them and - the local wardens warned us to keep away from shrapnel but anybody could go out and look at the ze}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8934838\charrsid19052 p}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 pelins because they moved so slowly that providing they were not coming in your direction they were quite a spe
ctacle. The school I was supposed to go to in London was hit with a bomb but - it was a sensation in those days but by comparison with what we saw in the last war of course there was no comparison.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 How long were you in London?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Only eight months - I've forgotten how many but months. The first air raid - the first zeppelin was brought down b}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8934838\charrsid19052 y Lieutenant Warnford in an air}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 plane - the night that we left.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 How many brothers and sisters did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 One sister - seventeen months younger.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 How old was your father when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
I can't really - I - remember - because I never knew his birthday. I knew - I knew which - the day of the year, we always celebrated his birthday but I didn't know how many years when he was born. But about thirty-five.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 He would be about thirty-five?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 And he came from Grangemouth.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 What was his job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 He was a ship's joiner. I think he had served his apprentices - his apprenticeship as that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did he have another job before or after he became a ship's joiner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
Well no job before to the best of my knowledge. But - he - when we moved from - he - they moved - originally from Glasgow Liverpool. He came from Grangemouth, then they went to Glasgow and mother and he came to Liverpool and
 he took a job in Tillotsons as a packer. It was a - because he could - a more settled job than the one - a ship's joiner. But less pay but it was more settled.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 This was more or less a semi-skilled job wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes, that's right - by compariso
n with his previous skilled job and the rate would be lower. He got twenty-one shillings a week - that was his wages then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 As a semi-skilled worker?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 As a semi-skilled packer. He had to pack - pack special stuff for Tillotsons, they cardboard box
 people to send to the Far East - they had a lot of trade in the Far East.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did he have any other casual or part time jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 He died in 1916?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Do you ever remember your father being out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 How old were you when your mother was born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 How?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 How old was your mother when you were born - sorry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
That's quite all right. I think it would be about thirty-three - but she didn't know her own age. No, because she came from a little village called
 Finnyfoot - opposite Iona, it's in the Isle of Mull in the Hebrides and - they - they had - the parents died and two brothers went on the emigration ship from Mull to America. One brother was pt into the Marines and my sister came - to - Glasgow I think 
or somewhere in Anyllshire first and then to Glasgow in domestic servants. She was what they called then in those days a sort of companion.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 That would be different to domestic service wouldn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Well - they had all the ideas of different - stat
us in domestic service. The polite way of calling it but she'd be too young to be a housekeeper, see, but they called her a companion. They were nice family, they thought - the people family in Kelvingrove Glasgow, very nice family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Is that the only place she worked at before she was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16457928 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did she have any jobs after she }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16457928 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Any part time jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No. I should say perhaps that after becoming a widow in 1916 and returning to Liverpool from London as I've already
 mentioned she went to work as a cloakroom attendant in Coopers at fifteen shillings a week.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Any idea what her hours were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 I - I think she was there about half past seven in the morning, she had to open the cloakroom before they opened the - sh
op. And when the shop finished, after the shop finished.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did she come home in the meantime?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 She was on the job all the time then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 All day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Is that the only job she had?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 It was, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Until she died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes. That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Who looked after the children while your mother was at work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
Well - we were then, that is in 1916 - we were then - I was - twelve. And I remember that we went to school, my sister and I went to school. Raced home from school which was a
 fair distance from home and - bought our dinners in a cook shop in Blessington Road. Could get good - relatively good meals. They were good things, they were dinners, what I would say a dinner would mean sort of - roast heart, you'd get a roast heart for
 fourpence.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Would you bring that home then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes, yes. No, bring it home, not eat it on the premises, and then go back to school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 You used to buy the heart and eat it on the premises?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No, at home. Blessington Road is right by where we lived you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 How many rooms were there in the house near Blessington Road?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Well - they were all four roomed houses.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 There would be no reception rooms then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No. Two bedrooms and a - a living room, we called that the front kitchen and a back kitchen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did anyone else besides your parents and sister live in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Other relatives or lodgers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did your mother pay anyone to help in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Was the washing done at home or sent out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
At home. In Egremont - in Liverpool after 1916 - she took in the job of washing huckaback towels for coopers, it was a little extra money. And we had a washing boiler in the back kitchen. And the wash - the water tap and the sink were in the backyard. I 
used to do those towels and I still detest huckaback.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 What's huckaback?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 It's a kind of material which when it gets wet goes very slimey and it's hard to get clean. Well it's hard wearing. I don't see them now.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did your mother or father mend or make the family's clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Mother made some clothes and bought the remainder new.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 She never bought them secondhand?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No. They were bought when she had enough money saved.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Where were they bought, have you any idea? Any market in the area or shops?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 For special things like my suits she came over to Liverpool. Because she could get a better selection.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 That's when she lived in Egremont?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes. I don't recall otherwise but father always cobbled our footwear. And it was bought new and cheap.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 And he always cobbled it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes. He used to buy belting. The shops in the old days well they had all - leather - oily belting.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 What is belting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Belting is - from a machine shop and the various factories the belts get 
stretched - and they drive the machinery, get stretched and they sold 'em to some place that used to cut them up into pieces and people did their own cobbling used to buy these pieces. They were rather a sting because they were soaking in oil.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did your father help your mother with any of the jobs in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
Father did the decorating. He lit the fire in the morning before he went to work. And he made - being a joiner - and taking some pleasure in actual - handicraft - handwork with joinery, he 
made - food safe, he made a step ladder - we still have these, and a salt box and he made a table which when mother was disposing of the home the - chaps who - to whom she sold the home said that that was worth more than all the rest, so he gave her thirt
y shillings for all the rest but she wouldn't part with the table. Made a medicine cabinet etcetera.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did he dress, undress or bath you - read to you, tell you stories?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 I don't remember if he dressed me. But he took me out - do you want details of
 my father? I have another little bit on connection with that. But - he - I don't remember when - if he ever dressed me but mother told me that I was then bow legged and he went down to the shore every evening and bought - brought up a bucket of seawater 
w
ith which my mother massaged my legs to straighten them. And I am not bow legged. My father he - he used to take me out to the shore and promenade to watch the ships, sailing ships and steam ships going up and down the river and he told me tales about the
m
. He also took me with him to catch fish by laying what we would call lay lines or tide lines on the sandbanks at low tide and coming back just before the next low tide to collect the lines and collect the fish catch. We caught anything from twenty to fif
t
y plaice, flukes, whiting and occasional sole which was reserved for mother. In between he took me with him to - when he dug for lug worms to use as bait because he said that when he turned the sand clumps over my keen sight was like a seagull. And I coul
d
 spot the worms better than he. The gulls followed us from hole to hole and sometimes caught a worm that I missed to my chagrin. I helped him to prepare the worms as bait and to bait lines later at home. He also taught me to fish with throw out leggel lin
e
s, sometimes from the waters edge and sometimes from the prom - fixed to a cane with an alarm bell on the top. All catches above family's current need were shared out free to the neighbours. If mother was out, a rare occurrence, and father was in, he look
ed after us. That's the answer to the next part.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did you - have any tasks you had to carry out regularly at home to help your mother and your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes, regularly I swilled the yard Saturday morning. Washed the back kitchen floor, it was tiled
, and was upgraded to wash the outside of the windows sitting on the sill of upstairs ones. Up to ending school that was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 That sitting on the sill is something you don't see now isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No, you never see it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 At one time women used to sit on the sills Saturday morning didn't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
Yes, that's right. That's right. Never see it now. I think it gave me a good head for heights for later mountaineering. Yes, I've been - I like mountaineering.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 How long did you continue to do these tasks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
Up to the time of finishing school - I did those, but I don't remember doing them after. Although swilling the yard and odd jobs I did after but mother was at home then and she used to do the jobs you see. My sister had regular job. As befitted he
r age but I don't remember what they were. My sister and I did help each other when possible. Played together when in the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did you help her in various ways?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Various things - I can remember we got on very well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Were you expected to go to bed at a certain time in your schooldays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
Yes, we were called in from street play at a regular time to go to bed. In early school days and later we were expected to be back home at certain times which I forget.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did your mother or anyone else put you to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
I don't remember ever being put to bed. Or - or at what age I put myself to bed. But I do remember either or both mother and father coming up to char - to chastise the gigglers as they called us. I suppose we were giggling and not goi
ng to sleep or else to comfort us - I - I have vivid recollection of them coming up to comfort us when I had toothache or neuralgia or nightmares.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did you share the bedroom or bed with anyone?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 I shared my bed - bedroom with my sister. And my father and mother slept in the front bedroom.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 That's the sleeping arrangement of the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 That's right - my sister and I in the back bedroom and my mother and father in the front bedroom.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 How long did that go on for - at what age did that arrangement cease?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 I think it would be somewhere about - twelve or thirteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Your father would be dead then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 He'd died then, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 What room did you bath in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 We bathed in the kitchen - in a zinc galvanized bath. On the hearthrug in front of the fire every Friday night.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 When did you have clean clothes to put on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Every week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Where did the family have their meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 In the living room we called the front kitchen. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Were there any occasions when you ate in another room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Where did your mother cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 In the back kitchen on the fire range and later on a gas cooker - also on a ring.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 When was breakfast eaten - did your father have his breakfast before he went out or did he take it with him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
No, before going to school we had ours and - in me father's case, before he went to work. I forget the details but I remember mother cooked porrid}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10380228\charrsid19052 ge after over night soaking of o}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 atmeal and we had cocoa - to drink.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 That's in the mornings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Your father would already have had his breakfast by then would he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes. Oh aye, he'd gone.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did you have anything different on certain days such as Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes, on Sunday often salt fish - breakfast. And the only meat of the week, the remains of which were served up for Monday dinner.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 That was on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Aye. That was the meat was on a Sunday. And a cake at teatime.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 On a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 What were the meals like on other days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Well mother made sheep
's head broth and shin bone broth. Sometimes made brawn from sheep's head which we call pottakeeks. Pottakeeks. I think it's Scotch - I think it's a Scotch name for brawn. There was quite a number of - of things which were rather Scotch because - I didn't
 know at that time but I later learned that these were particularly Scottish characteristics or terms. The general upbringing was Scottish. Scotch pancakes was one of the things and stewed rhubarb with bread and butter. We bought pork dripping.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Was it bread and butter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
No - margarine. But we did have butter for mother. Yes. Because mother - hadn't it was deemed that - she was mostly wanted having the butter you see. Not because of her insistence on it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Because you insisted?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Well - I think me father did. She had butter and we had marga}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10380228\charrsid19052 ri}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 ne. We used to call it double overweight from Maypole. I used to go and shop. And we used our own beef dripping but we bought pork dripping outside and used our own beef dripping. We - all this was very mu
ch esteemed I might say and we finished with rice or ground pudding - ground rice puddings with rhubarb or jam. Suet puddings also with apple and also stewed figs or prunes from dried ones.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 You've given me a pretty good idea of what the meals were like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
Oh some of it. I don't think the womenfolk would think that what I've told you was anything like adequate but I'm naturally telling you the things that I would think of as first class. When those were the - when those were the meals they'd stay a
s I liked in my mind - and they still do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did your mother or father bake their own bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes, she sometimes made her own bread. I remember taking it and getting it cooked - baked in the bake}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10380228\charrsid19052 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 house. It used to be customary to take the bread in tins and - and they baked it for you. She did bake occasionally in her own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did she make her own jam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Bottle fruit or vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Make pickles - wine or any medicines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No, I only remember stewed prunes and figs and rhubarb.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Was any beer brewed for the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did your father or mother grow their own vegetables and fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No, had no garden.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did they buy any - was it tinned?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 They bought dried fruit and the tinned fruit for visitors. I often -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 What do you mean tinned fruit for visitors?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
Well - tinned fruit - if you bought that that was just because we - we'd be having visitors. Special occasion you see and - I wouldn't know why but I suppose tinned fruit was esteemed - a special thing for visitors you probably had the same. Aye, well -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 They were pineapple chunks.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Oh yes, that's right. Quite a lot of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 My father always said they were turnips.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes. Ah yes. I can remember often being sent to - for a pennyworth of pot herbs for the broth.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 What did that consist of?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 And I believe now that you wouldn't get anything like as much value for one and six.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 What were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Well at that time you'd get carrots and turnips and a bit of leek and a
 bit of thyme - even put a bit of thyme and - celery. All normal vegetables.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 And these were all wrapped up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No. No. She - the lady in the shop would go to each one and pull out a - pull out the carrots or a - a little bit of turnip, cut off a b
it of turnip or - celery. Penn'roth of pot herbs - she'd make up what was deemed to be a pennyworth.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 How many times a week did you eat meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Only once. On Sundays. Home cooked.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 It was fresh then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did you ever get any extra meat such as rabbit from poaching?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No, only - only fish as I've mentioned already, the fish that we caught.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Do you remember seeing your mother having less food so that the family could have more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Well I can't remember but I strongly suspect it. But that's only from later - later on. Can't remember noticing it at the time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did your father have more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 That's - I can't remember that either. But I would strongly suspect it. Because he was sort of custom to see that your dad was - looke
d after, he had to go out to work and that was a harder job than the rest of us had.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Were you allowed to talk during meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes, we could talk, but not with our mouth full.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Could you choose what you wanted to eat from what was cooked or did you have to eat a bit of everything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
We ate everything that was put before us and took turns for the privilege of scrapping the custard dish or the pudding dish. Etcetera. Never left anything unless ill which caused alarm. We could always ask for something if justifiable.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 If there was any?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 What was your parents attitude if you left some food uneaten on the plate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Well that would cause alarm. We certainly wouldn't leave anything. We hardly left the pattern on the plate.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
If there was something on the table you wanted like the salt could you ask someone to pass it to you or did you have to wait until it was offered to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Oh that's what I meant when I said you could always ask for something if justifiable. I had read that one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 You could ask for it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Oh yes, you could always ask for anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Could you ask for a second helping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Well - always had a share out of the second helping if there was any available.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Were you expected to hold your knife and fork in a certain way and sit in a certain way?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes, we were taught to hold and use our knife, fork and spoon correctly and to sit facing the table.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Could you bring toys or a book to the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 When could you leave the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
Well - when we finished we would say, please may I leave the table? And we were given permission unless there was another tit-bit coming up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 In which case you wouldn't have asked in the first place?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Oh well we wouldn't know - know - we w
ouldn't know there was another tit-bit you see. And we would get a pleasurable surprise to know that we couldn't leave the table so we'd look then what was the tit-bit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did all the family sit at the table for the meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Only on Sundays or holiday
s. But on working and school days times varied. Hence father left before breakfast - before our breakfast and he arrived home after our tea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did you always sit at the same places at table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 We usually sat at the same place, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 How was the meal served and by whom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Mother served meal - the meal. And in order to share out properly no special order of service was followed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 None whatever?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Where was your sister fed before she could feed herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Don't remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 She was so near your age?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 That's right - I don't remember - I can only remember her feeding with me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Was your mother an easy person to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes, very easy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did she show affection?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Very affectionate.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 If you had any worries could you share them with her or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes, we could share - our - ours with her and she could share hers with us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Was your father an easy person to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes, we - only we - we - held him a bit more in awe but we could always talk to him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did he show affection?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes, love and respect for both.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 You could share your worries with him could you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes. Yes, to the best of my recollection I - anything that ever was on my mind I could speak to him about it. But my moth
er would be the one I'd naturally speak to first.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 How did your parents expect you to behave towards them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 With love and respect.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did your parents bring you up to behave towards your sister in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Just with the same - same a
ffectionate and a degree of respect to women. Womenfolk in general - like all girls and so on. I was brought up to treat them with respect. Because they were women. I think we thought a little bit less of them. I don't know why but that was the sort of id
ea, you respect them because they were weaker than you. There was something a bit less about them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did they say you should hit back or not it another child hit you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 I don't recall ever being urged to retaliate by hitting back. And I did not do so
 normally until one day my anger boiled over to the astonishment and respect of a - a friend that had attacked me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 What kind of people do you think your parents hoped you'd grow up to be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Good citizens. If you mean in so far as jobs I - I was go
od at drawing and my father - and some of my work was exhibited. The school work was exhibited in an exhibition an the library. And I had a mechanical bent so my father wanted me to be a mechanical draughtsman. An ambition that his death tore through. I c
a
n tell you a little bit about that perhaps, might be of interest. As an illustration. Because of my mechanical bent I was presented with a Mechano set and my dad told me to design a box to put the parts in and he would make it exactly as I designed it. We
 
did so and it was a beautiful box. Everything fitted in. And each compartment perfectly. Too perfectly - I couldn't get them out with my fingers once they were in. My dad knew all along but he gave me my first lesson in practical draughtsmanship. He made 
a tool to get the things out easily.
