\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Well as I mentioned he - sort of - had workmates that he was interested.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Where did he see them - just at work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 At work mostly - I don't remember them coming to our house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Were friends ever invited into your home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes, one mutual friend - was - came regularly - about every fortnight.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 He was a friend of both your mother and father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 And a cousin. Cousin came - friend - about - every - alternated with them, the visit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Would they be offered anything to eat or drink when they came?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Oh yes, they always came to Sunday tea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 On any particular day or occasion, would it be only on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes, it was only on a Sunday because the friends themselves were working and Sunday was the normal visiting day because of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Would you say that the friends invited in were your mother's friends or your father's friends or friends of both of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Of both. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did friends call in casually without an invitation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No, not to my recollection - only neighbours.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Neighbours used to call in without an invitation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did your parents ever go out to visit friends or neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 People often tell us that in those days they made their own amusements?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 What do you think your parents did when they got together with their friends and neighbours - play cards, music?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Well it was customary for one of the young ones to be able to play the piano. Sometimes it was an older one but - one that was learni
ng to play and had developed up to a good enough standard to play and accompany the singers and everybody took a turn at singing. Or did a funny turn. Sometimes somebody had a funny bent.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Many people divide society into different social classes or gro
ups, in that time before 1918 did you think of some people belonging to one and some to another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
Well - we understood - the term working classes. Yes. Well we understood the term in our house - working classes. We belonged to the working classes and 
the people round us were working classes and the other side to the world were the people who represented the better off - well off classes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 And you would say that would be the difference?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Which group do you reckon you were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Working class.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 What sort of people belonged to the same class as yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
Well - we - my family were very - much opposed to snobbery and - whenever incidents - snobbish incidents arose I reflected their criticism and sort of assessed people even at
 that early age, assessed people quite independent of their circumstances, class or anything else, just according to how they behaved. Perhaps I don't make myself very clear? No, I see, I can understand it. But - you see how - you classify people - middle
 class - working class and aristocrats. You're putting them in different classes that way. Well you want me to put them -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 If you could give me an idea what you thought - what sort of people belonged to the other classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Well the working class we
re the folks that had to go to weekly wage, see. And my impression of middle class people was professional people. And of aristocrats was Lord Derby who owned and robbed us of our Bootle, etcetera. That's how we felt, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Even at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes. I think we had a copy of our old nobility - that gave us all the details of how his family had acquired this money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Can you remember being brought up to treat people of one sort differently from people of another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No, my family was - my pa
rents were strongly opposed to snobbish distinctions or class distinctions and themselves did - observe - an approach based on other standard altogether. If a person was nice and well behaved and - spike well or - or acted will in regard to relation to ot
hers that was - that was represented to them - a classification.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Were you ever told to touch your cap or show respect in some way to anybody?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No, only raise my hat to a lady.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Was there anyone you called Sir or Master?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Well I did always
 call the - schoolmaster Sir but I remember my father strongly saying that nobody should be called Sir accept an old man because the word Sir came from Sire. And I still thought that and had the same prejudice when I grew later-grew up myself later.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Do you remember anyone showing respect to your parents in these ways?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
Well - the - the children definitely showed respect to the elders. And - it was usually - sometimes it would be the use of the word Sir. See, more an attitude more than speech.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 In the area where you lived who were considered the most important people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
Well I think the people of the Avenue in one place thought that Mr Charlesworth who was a baker on the corner and had some interest in - the local politics, was the important
 chap. And the doctor was always considered important. And perhaps the minister by those - or the priest by those who went to church.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did you ever come into contact with these people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes, the - baker. Or the confectioner - yes. He seemed all right.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Why were they considered important do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
I think when it was a question of considering importance it would be assessed in this way. If you had a phone - it's required that a form should be filled in by some J.P. or a - or somebody 
to testify to anything well - a person who was qualified to fill that form in would be considered of some importance.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Who do you think the shopkeepers in the area associated with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Well - at first - before my father's death I really can't remembe
r except that one case, Mr Charlesworth. But later - after my father's death in Liverpool the - shop keeper was associated with a football club. I think it was Liverpool or Everton football club, I've forgotten. But - he was a fairly well known name.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Who do you think the clergy mixed up with? Did you have much to do with the clergy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 I'd nothing to do with them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Who did the teachers mix up with - who did they associate with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 The teachers at school do you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 In their spare time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 I - I don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did you come into contact with farmers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Or employers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 What sort of people would you say went to the church and to the chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Well - we were vaguely under the impression that they were al
l hipocrites. We were - I - we children were vaguely under the impression that they were all hypocities and - perhaps - many were but I subsequently learnt to appreciate that - some were not - definitely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Where you lived did all - the people in the wo
rking or lower class have the same standard of living or would you say there were different groups in the working class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Quite a number - were similarly placed to ourselves. But - sometimes where the - where the father drank - it led to trouble. I ca
n remember one opposite rather shocked me because he seemed quite a nice chap when he was not drunk but every Saturday he came back drunk and it horrified me to find that he could be so different. Well, it was things like that that would lower the standar
d. Our standard was low you see, there were others were higher in the same avenue. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Who would they be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Slightly better job because a bricklayer for example got better money. But a railway worker got less so his family would be even higher - h
arder - hard up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 How would that demonstrate itself - better clothing or better food or furniture?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Each way I think, clothing and furniture - and - food.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Do you think that one group felt itself superior to the rest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Oh - yes, yes. Some thought they were always a cut above others.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Who would they be?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 They'd be people in good settled jobs - with perhaps four to five shillings more and weekly income.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Were some families thought of as rough and others as respectable?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Ye
s, that's right, definitely. That was a classification more pronounced than the classification working class and middle class. Because the respectable ones often thought of themselves as middle class.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Do you remember a distinction of this kind between craftsmen and labourers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
Yes, there was a distinction. It was always - a craftsman was always deemed to be a but above the others but naturally the same applies, as I've said before, because his income would be higher.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did your mother and father have the same attitude to people in different classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes. Yes, definitely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did you think your mother saw herself as belonging to a particular social class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Oh she accepted that we were working class. No question.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Why do you think so - was she thinking of her parents, her home, or work, or your father - what gave her that idea do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Because - they were totally dependant upon a weekly wage.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 That was her criterion?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 That was the economic criteria - economic criteria, why you classify groups by their economic - standard.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Was it possible at that time to move from one group or one class to another? Can you remember anybody who did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Very - very - very slowly. Very slowly but it was possible. But what tend
ed to happen more would be that the children - older children when they started jobs would start joining a better class - better classification. Well that was a slower business. They didn't move certainly like nouveau riche. We call the nouveau riche toda
y. Nobody seemed to suddenly acquire riches.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Do you remember anyone being described as a real gentleman or a real lady?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes. The term was fairly commonly used. I can remember my mother describing me father as one of nature's gentlemen. Yes. She s
aid, nature's gentlemen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Why do you think that was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
I don't - well she thought that - people were - naturally disposed one way but under the force of circumstances they sometimes behaved another way. Well - one who was a gentleman could behave l
ike a gentleman it might suit his purpose to be so, he couldn't be one of nature's gentlemen but one who was a gentleman under all circumstances would be one of nature's gentlemen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Do you remember seeing a policeman around where you lived as a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes, regularly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 What did you think of him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
Well as policemen were used as bogey men - if we were doing anything wrong we would call out and give warning and look upon him rather - as a threat - but speaking generally I never feel - felt any 
- prejudice against policemen because many times I knew of incidents - where they were quite kindly and helpful and you could ask them questions you know. If you're in difficulties.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 When you were naughty did your mother ever say, I'll call a policeman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
No, I can't remember but that was very commonly done. I - I've heard it very often. But I never remember being threatened with a policeman by my mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 How do you think he treated people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Who?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 The policeman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Oh quite reasona
bly I think myself. Quite reasonable. My impression was that the they were not - sort of - throwing their authority around. They were much more - sort of seeking co-operation more.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Was your home rented?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did you see anything of the landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes - well - the collector landlord every week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 What did you feel about him as a landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Well - he was one of the bigger - biggest bogey's of life. Because a quarter of you - your income went to the landlord.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Do you remember feeling that your parents had to struggle to make ends meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 What did you think about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
Well I thought that that was just - accepted that as part of life. But always sort of lived in a hope - as they did - that things would go better. Because hope played quite a big part in their lives.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 What difference did it make to the family when your father was ill or out of work? Was he ever ill or out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 I don't remember him being too ill to go to work. Except when he died.
 And that - he actually took ill at work. I might mention as you might be interested in something in that connection that my father collapsed at work and was rushed to hospital. He actually had had a perforation and - himself being suspicious that doctors
 
and hospitals used poorer people for experimentation he declined to stay in hospital. So or have his op - or have an operation and they sent him home at his own request. But I think now after twenty-five years working in a hospital, even in a humble ancil
l
ary capacity, I've learnt enough to know that he should have gone immediately to hospital and had his operation. He would have been all right because in other respects he was healthy and he would have recovered and no surgeon would have experimented with 
him. For two reasons, one - a perforation is not a suitable case to experiment with and secondly all any surgeon would have been quite proud to have pulled him through that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 What difference did it make to the family when your father was ill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Well
, as he died, from the only illness that I can recall that stopped him from going to work, it made a tremendous difference. Well insofar as the house had to be sold up and we had to move away elsewhere. That was a new life altogether. Even though a short 
time in London, that was a new life - the war was on, zep}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7160926\charrsid19052 p}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
elin raids and - and one thing and another but that - we came back again, the war was still on in Egremont and conditions were very severe.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 You went down to London to your father's people did you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes, that's right. To the grandfather.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did you ever get any help from the Guardians or the Parish? Or any charity?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 When there was someone in the district whom the people disapproved of very strongly was there any special way i
n which they showed it - do you remember anybody being made to leave by rough music and if so what for - was an effigy ever made?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No, I don't remember anybody being pill}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7160926\charrsid19052 ar}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 ed - I don't know quite what rough music means - it's a new expression to me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 If an Orangeman came to live amongst Roman Catholics or visa versa then they'd make it pretty hot for him wouldn't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes, that's quite 1 quite possible, but I never lived in a - a street where the antagonism between Catholics and Protestants 
was that high. Although, as a little boy, I can remember being on the Protestant side and throwing stones across a big waste ground at another crowd that looked very much the same as ours and they called them Catholics. Or they called them Rednecks. Had a
ll sorts of names for them. But I just like the throwing of the stones because I was skilled at throwing stones, that's all. Although I never reached them with mine - I was too small then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 It was practically impossible for a Protestant to get into a Catholic area and a Catholic to get into a Protestant area wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
That's quite possible, but I actually never particularly noticed that. But I will say this, that you could rent a house quite easily when we went to Bootle. Quite easily. They were vacant all over the place.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 There was generally one house in a street wasn't there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 In a street, oh yes, there was always one or two - yes. And they sometimes put a couple of hyndred}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7160926\charrsid19052 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 weight in free if you took the house. And unbelievable thing now. Yes, oh yes. A woman was brought in to clean it out for you. It's almost unbelievable now.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Where were we up to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 This last one about where people disapproved. I don't remember anybody being harmed in any way - the only example was what I told y
ou about - the Germans. With mob war fever. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Were you given lessons by your parents - you weren't were you? How old were you when you first went to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 I think it was five.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 When you first started what time in the morning did you go and when did you come back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Well - I think we went to nine - nine o'clock. Came back at dinner time, mother met us, took us back and brought us back again to school.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 She took you there in the morning did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 That was early on - in Bootle. Now I think I have mentioned to you that I - the first day I went to school, I mentioned that earlier.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 How long did it take you to get to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 The first school would take - about four minutes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did you come home for your midday meal?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 What did you think of school - did you like it or dislike it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 The first - day - I didn't like it but I - I grew to like school and always did afterwards.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 How did you feel about the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 I liked most of them. Nearly all -
 nearly all. There was only one man who had a massacre - a sadistic - streak in him and he used to cane us across - below - above or I should say above the palm of the hand and it hurt mostly on the wrist and he had a bad name amongst us. But I don't reme
mber any other teacher like him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did the teachers emphasi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7160926\charrsid19052 z}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 e certain things as important in life - such as manners, tidiness, punctuality or ways of speaking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes, almost all the teachers stressed the same - had the same ethical standard. Which co
incided very much with my parents. Fitted in all right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 If you did something the teachers disapproved of what would happen? How did they punish the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Well - in the early days they punished you with the cane.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 For what crime would you be caned?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Persistent mischievousness. Usually tea - if they were teasing - if children were teasing each other. Persist}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7160926\charrsid19052 en}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 tly and interfering with the progress of the class. I don't - I don't remember really all the crimes but most - most that I comm
itted were met by writing out so many lines. But I didn't have many - I wasn't often occasion - punished - needed punishing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Were girls treated the same as boys for punishment do you know?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 I don't think so but I don't remember because I didn't -
 I wasn't in their classes of course but - I don't remember my sister speaking of any - punishment other than writing out lines.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did your parents show an interest in your schoolwork?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes, they always enquired what we were - and we had reports.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did they ever visit the school to meet the teachers at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 I can't remember them ever visiting - no. Although - I will say my mother, when I was lit - I left school - well during the war -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 I'm dealing with your first school now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Oh first school, O.K. that's all right then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did she ever visit the first school at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Well I wouldn't remember really. I know she took us to school so the chances are that she did know some of the teachers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did the other children come from similar types of home to your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes, very similar.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did the teachers single out some children for different treatment from the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 I don't remembe}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7160926\charrsid19052 r any general favourit}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 ism. Only odd - odd cases.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Were there any gangs or groups in the school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Well we made our own gangs in the schoolyard.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 What kinds of gangs would they be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
Well - in general with - similar sort of interests. Some that played cricket and some that played football and that some that were interested in w
hatever was the current cowboy and Indian type of gang warfare - but it didn't last very long that because it was only playtime. It's a reflection of what happened at night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did you go to another school afterwards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Well I went to - three schools. One in Bottle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 How long were you there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 I was up there for about - I think it's so many to - 1906 wasn't it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Was Bootle your first school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Which was the second one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Second one was Riverside school in Egremont.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 How long did you go there for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 I think it was - one - I've forgotten the actual dates now but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 How old would you be when you went there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 War was declared while I was there. I think - I have an idea of getting the dates earlier on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Were the hours the same as the other school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes, the best of my recollection. All the hours -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 What sort of school was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 It was an ordinary - Corporation - - Corporation school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 What was the first one - was that a board school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Gray Street school, yes, still there. Bootle. Do you call them board schools?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Well there's board schools, private school, church school - day school or a boarding school.;
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 I see - oh a board school is not a boarding school, I see. Oh well, that's
 right, a board school, that's quite right. Well, the three of them were the same type of school - the other was Steer Street in Liverpool. In Everton yes, that's right. Well that was after my father's death - the other two were before.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Were they all somewhat similar?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes, very similar.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 And would your opinion of the teachers be the same at the three schools?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Well, my opinion wouldn't be worth tuppence for the first school because I was too young, I'm quite - in the second school the - 
with the exception of that teacher I mentioned to you who had a bit of a sadistic streak in him, all the others were good teachers. And in the case of the last school they were first class teachers - and the headmaster was first class. I might say if it's
 
- if I'm permitted to say now - I finished top of the school in the last exam and he sent for my mother and asked her if she could put me to a scholarship. But she was only earning fifteen shillings a week and I was getting - bringing in three and six a w
e
ek for nights and Saturdays then and that was too low an income. She - to put me to boarding school - to put me to a college. So I - went to work. I might mention in that connection that he was a first class headmaster and she had seen him once before in 
another connection. In that the authorities were encouraging young boys to do useful jobs - in connection with the war where there were shortages and as I had learnt to cobble, I'd learnt}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7160926\charrsid19052 
 from my father the art of cobbling}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 . I did some cobbling and I cobbled
 a pair of the headmaster's shoes so well that he brought some more. But my mother went and protested. She said that that was enough. That I'd done one good pair - done them very well but she knew the amount of work that had gone into it and declined to h
a
ve any more done. Not for money or anything. Just that it was a - she thought it was imposing. And he accepted that in good spirit. Oh quite - he was very good. He became the headmaster of Anfield Road afterwards. Had a very good reputation and - but he d
ied fairly young.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Would you have stayed longer if you'd had the opportunity?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes, oh aye. I could have got -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did you attend any part time education afterwards - say evening classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes, I - I went to night school in some form or anot
her 'til I was about forty-five. Yes. I enjoyed school so much that - I went to - sort of commercial courses because it was associated with the job and even technical courses because I was interested th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7160926\charrsid19052 em but - later on I went to sort}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052  of W.E. classes and N.C.L.C. classes - until I finally took them -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 What}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7160926\charrsid19052 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
s the N.C.L.C.?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 National Council of Labour Colleges.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 WEA is workers Education Association isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Do you have any regrets about your education?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Well I feel that - I 
was wasted. From a social point of view - in that I had the capacities that were not used. Because opportunity to develop them was not there. But I don't feel sore about it or anything like that. I don't feel any a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7160926\charrsid19052 gr}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7160926\charrsid19052 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
ved. It's just because it's - it's the way the society - there's a lot of others the same as myself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Do you think you benefited from attending school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes, definitely. Oh aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 While you were at school did you have a part time job or any means of earning a little regular money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 How did you get the job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 One of my school mates told me about it. He did the same - similar.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 What exactly did you have to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Every Friday - every - night - from Monday to Friday on leaving school we went to school until six o'clock I think it was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 You went to school until six o'clock?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Went from school to - work. In my case I worked for a jeweler the Brown - Browns in London Road.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 What did you do there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 For half a crown a week. I polished silver with - French chalk and ammonia. And various other little jobs but that was one I remember most.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did you work on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Or Saturday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes, all day Saturday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 All day Saturday and every night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Sat - every - night - Saturday and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 While you were at school did you do a part time job or earn a little regular money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes, after 1916 I went to work at Brown's the jewelers in London Road.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 What did you do there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 I - I - I obtained the job through a school friend because several of them had nights and Saturday and jobs we used to ca}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7160926\charrsid19052 ll them. The job I did was to p}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
olish the silver with French chalk and ammonia and run messages. I think mostly to the engravers to get purchases engraved.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 To get purchasers names engraved on the things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
Yes, that's right, yes. By the way, as cobblers were in the Army - were all in the Army, we in school were encouraged to learn this cobbling and I already having been taught by my dad found myself so}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7160926\charrsid19052 il}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 ing and heeling the headmas
ters shoes. He was so pleased with the he brought more to be done for payment. So I might have had another part time job. But my mother thought it was too much work for me and told me to take them back and explain. The headmaster took it very well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did you do that job at the same time you were working for the jewelers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
I couldn't remember that. You mean this cobbling? No, going back to - going back to the jewelers - every school day we worked from four o'clock to 6 p.m. allowing for - about ten m
inutes to get from school to work and worked all day Saturday from nine 'til six. No Sundays. I think }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7160926\charrsid19052 W}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
en - I think Wednesday was a - a half day there so probably no - no Wednesday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did you get holidays with pay there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Well there was no such thing as that in a job like that of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 What were you paid?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
I was paid two and six a week. I had no way of - of telling - you were going to ask - I - I've - I've answered the questions because I've read them you see. And it's better for me to r
ead them a bit beforehand for accuracy. That's all you see. You'll have to add one or two things at the end because I feel I might have missed out something important.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 But did you feel the half a crown was a fair wage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 I didn't know - I didn't -
 there was no way of telling if it was fair or not but some chaps earned three and six in other jobs and I later looked for one and obtained it but that was a harder job so -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did you give any of the money to your mother?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes, I gave it all to m
other and she gave me back an increase in pocket money. But as her income was only fifteen shillings a week - her own wages - and a pound a month from my grandfather in London.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 You hadn't mentioned that before?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 I didn't - no, I'm sorry, that's o
ne of the things for example that I - I - I remember afterwards and missed and I should have - answered you that on one of the questions - I've forgotten which it was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Perhaps you could elu}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7160926\charrsid19052 c}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 idate now could you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes, very good. Well - the grandfa
ther - he didn't think like my father, he was a Freemason and a - anti-Catholic, anti-Jew, etc., etc., read the Bible every day, a piece of the Bible, page I think it was, every day - and he'd been through the Bible about three times - or four times in th
e
 course - up to then but - he had a strong sense of duty. He was a Customs Preventive Officer, that might explain it because your jobs tend to mould your character and - anyway he had a good sense of duty and I must give him credit - he sent a pound every
 month to my mother to augment her income. And that was very - helpful.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 That was quite a good sum in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes. Well at the time I'm talking about prices were rising with the war on and that together with her own wage - left us very tight s
o that my little wage - even though it seems so little now, would be quite a help.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 How did you get on with other people who you worked with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Well - doesn't it ask - what it went into - how you spent it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 How did your mother spend that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes. It went into the household pool and helped - helped to pay for the potato pies - tuppence each and sheep}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7160926\charrsid19052 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
s hearts, fourpence each that my sister and I had to buy from the cook shop when we rushed home from school. By the way there's a little point of
 interest of another school friend, giving you an idea. A school friend had a job which involved collecting full size - a full size milk churn in a two wheeled hand truck - near school and pushing it to a dairy at the corner of Lansfield Road and Stanfiel
d
 Road every dinner time. This was half way home for me so we teemed up and alternate days we would take turns in the shafts while the other rode with the churn. It was a big wheeled, well balanced, hand platform truck or trolly and we could run with it. I
 
left him at that dairy and ran on home. The distance from school to home would be about one and a quarter miles. It was not usual to be as far from school but we started in Steer Street school when we came back from London and lived in a friends lodging w
hich was nearer to the school near to the school. But when mother obtained a four roomed house further away in Nessfield Street, she did not like - nor did we like to leave the school. Hence the distance between the home and the school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did your sister go to the same school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 How did you get on with the other people you worked with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 I got on very well. There was only a couple of assistants and the boss and his wife.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 How did you get on with the boss - how did he treat you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
Quite well - I don't recall feeling anything - any - for or against - pro or con sort of feelings concerning him but I remember that his wife laughed at and with me once when she said to nobody in particular - I've got nerves. And I - not understa
nding the implication took it literally and said to her, well, everybody's got to have nerves.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 How did you feel about the job - did you like it or did you dislike it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 I was interested. It was a new world to me. It was quite a change from school
 and I remember being very proud to pass the half crown to my mother as my first mainly earnings. Like I imagined a savage would feel - a savage youth would feel when he brought home his first tiger. It made you into a man - a status symbol. A liked schoo
l just as much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did it alter your attitude to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No, I liked school just as much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did you do any other part time jobs before you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes, as I said before.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 What were they - how did you get the second one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 I got
 that one through a school friend and it was delivering bread from Croppers in Hayworth Street to the customers and a full load to another shop - another general shop in Rosscommon Street.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 What hours did you work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 The bread - perhaps I should ex
plain a couple of things. The bread truck was like a rectangular box on end with two small wheels at the bottom and two handles at the top and was wheeled by balancing it on the two wheels and pushing. The top end was the lid. I also washed the big window
 
every Friday night and did odd jobs in the shop when not delivering and I served the customers later whilst the manager made the cocoa for us both, aye, there's a little thing here perhaps that reflection of the time. Although the - I was very proud about
 bringing that first half crown home, the proudest moment that I ever felt was during the - 1914 war when coal was very short. With this cold winter and we had to burn old boots, wood and even bits of furniture were burnt, that was spareable an}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3673613\charrsid19052 d sometimes no fire despite persistent}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052  touring of coal}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7160926\charrsid19052 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 yards. When I found one day I found a coal}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7160926\charrsid19052 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 yard with coal -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Could you explain what a coal}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7160926\charrsid19052 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 yard is?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Well at the ends of odd streets, say every three or four street, there would at that time be a dairy and
 somewhere else, another street, about the same number of coal yards. And coal was delivered in quantities to these yards and people could buy the coal direct from the yard. And sometimes took it home - I think it was cheaper in a case like that. Instead 
of accepting delivery. Mostly later I can recall the coalman going down the middle of the street and shouting coal and you just bought it off the cart. I remember - a joke when I was a kid that puz}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3673613\charrsid19052 zled me but I thought very funn}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 y when I was little. A coalman had a sign saying - a la carte one price, and then cul-de-sac another price.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Do you ever remember the saying act soft and I'll buy you a coal}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3673613\charrsid19052 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 yard?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Well but where you had a group of four roomed houses built, say at the turn of the cen
tury or 1890. They always used to build a bit of a shed at the end of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Brick one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 This was generally let to the house - the person who occupied the end house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 And this was generally the coal}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3673613\charrsid19052 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 yard.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 And it was generally shaped like a piece of cheese because it used to straighten the whole lot off.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Well you've explained to me now - what I can confirm. I remember seeing that but I didn't know that about the tiele. But it was very oft
en the end of a street - it was a gable end and sometimes the entry ran down the side of it to go round the back of all the others and the gable end and the other street house was the first one as you came round the corner - in their backyard.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 And you'll find this in any small street.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 And your story about dairies?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 They were quite a feature in Liverpool up to the beginning of this war - the last war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes. They had their own cow you know, and they milked the cow. And
 sometimes the cow got a - a - ran away and gave us all a fright. Got loose and the - street and gave the children a fright. I do remember in our - in my own case but I remember my wife says that happened with her and frightened the wits out of her and sh
e still is frightened of cows she said on account of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
I remember that I had a little job once - well my pal had one it was a dairy and he had to deliver milk - it wasn't delivered in bottles it was in a churn
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes, that's right, in a churn, yes. They fished it out and delivered it in a jug.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
He had to milk the cow to get the milk out of it so he could go deliver it at night time. Well when he - we were business like and we decided to get a few more customers you see so we had half a dozen 
customers of our own and we couldn't get any more milk out of the cow we got it off the tap.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 You sort - of diluted the milk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Exactly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Well that wasn't done now, even in those days. I think when - that was done even off the cart - the milk 
churns, yes. By the way I was - I was telling a story, I nearly finished it - it's quite all right, but on one occasion when it was very hard to get coal I succe}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3673613\charrsid19052 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 ded in getting this quarter of coal. A quarter's twenty-eight pounds I forgot for the moment -
 once before I mentioned a different figure but I know it was a quarter of coal and I took it home, lit a fire and - when my mother came home from work the proudest I can ever remember was opening that - whole place door and showing her those black diamon
ds. We knew the meaning of it then. My sister and I both opened it and showed her and she was thrilled to bits.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Can we talk about this job you had with the baker?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Do you remember what a jockey was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes, the jockey was the little bit extra that you put on top. In fact that was done in this shop.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 In every shop?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
Yes, I - even as a boy when I served bread - the manager - would be at the back making the cocoa - it was only then that I served it for him - we put a little bit of half a barn cake on or something like that as a jockey.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 That was to safeguard themselves in case the bread was underweight?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Had dried up, yes. If it went a bit stale it lost its moisture and the weight would alter so they covered themselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Quite often it was generally a bun wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 It was - I can remember - often about - but half a bar cake - half a bar cake, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did you work there on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No, it was the same hours as the previous job. But it was nearer to school - four til}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3673613\charrsid19052 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
 six every evening. I've an idea there was some sort of - government regulation that they couldn't employ you after six. At that age. That's why it was six. Well I wouldn't be too certain about this now but - I do definitely remember them 
saying that - they couldn't employ me after a certain time - later than a certain time. And I have the idea it was six o'clock. It might have been half past six, I wouldn't swear. Buy that's the sort of thing that could be checked always on regulations. T
hey worked me to the time allowed at that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did you work on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Oh no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Saturday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Saturday all day. I think it was half day Wednesday then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did you have any holidays with pay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Oh no holiday like that in that job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 What were you paid?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Three and six a week. By comparison with the previous job I was a big fellow. But it was a harder job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 What did you do with the money - give it to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 I gave it to me mother just as previously but she increased me pocket money but I've forgotten now how much it was by then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 How did you get on with the other people you worked with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Quite well, the boss was - the boss was not the owner - he was only the manager. But I liked him and he like me. He
 said I was an old head on young shoulders. He slaked out coffee - slaked out the coffee so well that it was like the present day drinking chocolate and awe drank with our barn cakes. I liked this.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 How did you feel about the work - did you like it or dislike it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
I didn't mind the hardness of the work but I did not care for two things. One was the size of the shop window when cleaning it on a, Friday night, and another unstable ladder on a windy day - a windy night. And the other was taking a load
ed bread truck down Rupert Hill and Rosscommon Street - both steep hills when ice and snow was on the ground. By the way I've since seen that window. The districts in the course of demolition but I've since seen that window it's just broken in one corner 
but otherwise - as I had washed it and I quite agree with myself as a boy that it was a big window.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did that job alter your attitude to work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 To school? Oh no, I still liked school but I felt that I was a man. You felt - blowing out your chest - 
blowing out and your head swells when you - got a job. As compared with - bringing any income in.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 When you were a kid it was your ambition to get a job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 It was a status symbol - that's right. By the way, a thing that might be of interest to us.
 I taught myself shorthand before leaving school when was at home and I later used it after leaving school to take dictation for letters and report political speeches and minutes of meetings, etc. Pitmans seemed to lend itself to teach - self teaching.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did you do any other part time jobs before you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 What was your first full time job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 I was a customs clerk in shipping office. Kings Irvings, the Clan Line.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 How did you get that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Through the Juvenile Employment O
ffice. Local Education Authority. I asked for a shipping clerks job because a pal, a neighbour, was one and he recommended it. However previous to leaving school the headmaster Mr Fred Bradley at Steer Street school asked my mother to come for a chat and 
h
e told her that he would like to put me in for a scholarship. However she could not afford to allow that as he well understood. I finished top boy of the school according to his testimonial. He told me to come back to see him after the interview for a shi
p
 - this shipping clerks job which I duly did. And when I told him that I'd been engaged at seven and six a week with a promise to increase to ten shillings very soon he said, come back and see me and if they're long about give - that is, if they're long a
bout giving you that ten shillings. I didn't need to go back but I did speak to him later on the top deck of a tram. I thought - all of us thought him a great chap.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 What exactly did you have to do in the job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 I started as an office boy - copying 
typed letters into a book of transparent paper leaves by placing a wax sheet of one side of the leaf in the book and a damp cloth between the leaf and the wax sheet and then placing a typed letter facing the other side of the leaf. Then closing the book a
n
d putting it in a press and revolving the screw at the top to get pressure. Later I was moved up to the Bombay department as customs clerk. Which involved completing papers for any cargo where required and taking them along to the custom house and getting
 
them passed customs. I also had to call on various shipping agents in addition I had to collect and dispatch the whole of the office post. I was sacked for forgetting to post three very important letters, having left them on the post desk in a rush to go 
home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 What hours did you work there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Nine to five and nine to twelve Saturday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No Sunday work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did you have any holidays with pay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 A weeks holiday a I think with pay to the best of my recollection but I'm not - Saturday was the half-day.
