\insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 I am a fool. However, I've enjoyed life so far and I think it is good to be alive even as a stoic and hope to have a few more mellow philosophical ye}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14381726\charrsid19052 a}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 rs to gee the young ones into making a socialist world community if war permits them to do so. Is that all right. Is that dragging in too much of the present political attitudes.;
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did you continue to live at home after you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
Oh yes. I used to tread a great deal - rather - very fond of reading and rather serious and novel literature - both. And I continued model engineering - that was my hobby. And I went to night school on commercial c
ourses whilst I was working in a shipping office but I changed to technical courses after that. I joined the I.L.P. and attended political and economic and philosophy courses at the National Council of Labour colleges and at the Workers Education Associat
i
on. I did courses in French and Spanish language up to Royal Society of Arts certificate standard in the later and took educational courses, non vocational, until I was almost forty years age - of age - of old - forty years old. Because I enjoyed learning
 I must say. I always lived at home except for short periods when I was manning a stand in the British Industry's Fair each year for a couple of weeks.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did starting full time work change your relationship with your parent at all? Or with your sister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No. Up-to 1928 - that's coming on later now, when mother had a stroke, that's cerebral }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14381726\charrsid19052 hemorrhage}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
. And in order that we could nurse her my sister went to work until dinner time only and I worked alternate - afternoons - I worked afternoons and evening
s only and - as an insurance agents job permitted me to do. That was for three years until she died. We didn't want her to go to hospital that's why - I nursed her in the morning and my sister nursed her after dinner.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did you spend your Sunday any differently?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes, I started to go rambling and fell walking on Sundays. And - political meetings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 You never went to church or chapel did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No. I still - still go rambling, as a matter of fact - on retiring from work at sixty-five, that's 
last year, my work colleagues gave me a typewriter and a pair of hiking boots each for my wife and - and myself and an anorak for her. I never went to church or chapel.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did you go out in the evenings just after you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Just a minute - I
 was under the impression that I didn't have anything to - yes. Have I? I - I was under the impression there was nothing to go from her afterwards.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 What difference did it make to your life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Oh I - I mixed with - friends at work - I - I've been p
laying bowls with them, they had a bowling team and I - mixed with - I had friends that I made as school and friends - neighbours from the street - Willie and - two friends from the street I went out regularly with. But that was before I went into politic
s. When I joined went into politics there was hosts of friends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Where did you go with these friends just after you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes. Well I thought - I had an idea I'd explained that. I did a lot of reading. And novel reading and I - I did model 
engineering. I went to night school. Did a lot at night school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did you go to any - theatres about that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Oh yes, I - I mentioned that when things got more comfortable - my mother - mother liked the opera and she liked Scotch concerts. And -
 we liked the cinema. We would look round for - a good picture, what we'd call a good picture and go to whichever cinema had that picture.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did you make any new friends at that time - boys or girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes, oh aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 How did you meet them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Through - through politics. Is this before I went into politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 SI want to keep it before 1918.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
Oh I see. O well in fairness - to be exact I couldn't say that I made a lot of new friends. No. I made one or two friends of people that I worked with - had - had a couple of school friends and two friends from the street I lived in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did you ever bring friends home to your mother and sister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Very rarely. Very rarely. But they knew who they were. They knew them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did you have any special friends at that time - boys or girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
I never had had any girl friends - never specially at that age, you see. But I have an idea that - my mother wanted me to mix more with others and we used to go on Saturday nights to social gatherings it was qui
te a common thing then for you to go down a street on a Saturday night and at least there'd be a house on one si}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14381726\charrsid19052 d}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
e or the other lit up and a piano playing and singing going on and that sort of thing and I used to go to those socials. And there would be gir
ls and fellows present there that I knew but sort of didn't mix up very much. In fact I can remember being a - holding up the end of the piano more often than not because I was a bit shy.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did your mother met your friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Oh yes, always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did she expect to know where you were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Well - I would always tell her where I was - where I'd been or where I was going.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did you have to be home before a certain time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did you have to be home by a certain time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No, there was
 no compulsory rule there - it was just automatic. You just said so. But sometimes I would be extra late. But that was all right. She would always sit up for us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 I don't think you took part in any political activities before 1918 did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 You've already explained what your present political activities are?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Any why you held that point of view?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 What was your sister's job before she }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16457928 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 She was a down quilt machinist. Yes. And her husband job - oh yes, quite a skilled job. Many variations on it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did she serve her time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
No. No. They taught them there. Morris' was the name of the firm in Bartlett Street I think it was or - some name like that. The back of Ludnor Road. Her husband Jock, he was - that's George - he was a tutor and an organi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14381726\charrsid19052 z}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 er in the National Council of Labour Colleges - 'til he retired in 1969, the same as myself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Did they have any children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 They had two girls and both of them are radiotherapists. They're close together and they worked - they're both }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16457928 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052  but they live fairly close together and they both work in the same hospital in Cheltehnam way. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 You had one sister - you told me about her - is she }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16457928 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Yes, that's right. And her husband and the two children. But my wife's job - her job before she was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16457928 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052  was a cashier in a Corporation Tramways department. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Which one was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Which one? Well she was in Hatton Garden and then she was posted out to Seaforth. In fact one of the 
reasons she - took over temporarily my insurance book and gave her other job up was because I didn't like her going out in the air raids. Picking up - picking up coppers, I mean, just checking up on the tramwayman's - takings in Seaforth. Because it was a
 
hot number, Seaforth, as you will recall. They were aiming for it all the time and I didn't like her doing that. But - later, she didn't like the insurance job - collecting job and she got a job as a pools clerk through her sister in law who was already i
n the - that job and she's been in that job for twenty-one years and just recently had a gold watch for twenty-one years service and they had a celebration. She retired last December. At least, retired from that job.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 I know who's not sixty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Oh n
o, no, she's quite - quite younger than that and she's - she - doesn't need to retire yet at all but - she thought she would like to retire now that I've retired. And - we might take on a part time job you know. Money - money is - I don't - I couldn't say
 I could go to the South of France now for my holidays - not with the present income. But we don't - she doesn't worry so much about the money at all. We don't mind living a bit - close. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 You had no children did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7634190 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 Anything else you have to tell me?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11674240 AR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14951568\charrsid19052 
