rage and also as a trade union supporter he was on St Georges Plateau, Liverpool, in 1911 on what was known locally as Bloody Sunday when thousands of strikers etc., were charged by police from an
other city. The sixth errors and omissions. Some events have been repeated but are in - are in the main substantially correct. Forgive an ageing man's cerebral chrysalis. Number seven, I have read the reprint of Dr Paul Thompson's article entitle Memory a
nd History with much interest and fully endorse his observations. The city bred working class of the period he seeks to cover did not have the benefit of a Robbie Burns to describe their life as accurately as he described the life of a land}{\rtlch\fcs1 
